ngland","Doveridge, Derbyshire, England":"Doveridge, Derbyshire, England","Eaton, Derbyshire, England":"Eaton, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Milward","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Millward  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Millward","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands): occupational name from Middle English <i>milne-ward</i>, <i>mille-ward</i> ‘keeper of a mill, miller’ (Old English <i>mylen-weard</i>). In southern England and the West Midlands this was a standard medieval term for a miller. Compare   Miller  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Milward was born in 1463, in Eaton, Derbyshire, England, his father, Robert I Milward, was 20 and his mother, Margery De Thick, was 20. He married Ann Kniveton about 1489, in Eaton, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1493, in his hometown, at the age of 30, and was buried in St Cuthbert's Church, Doveridge, Derbyshire, England."},"et":{"1463–1493":"1463–1493","1467–1503":"1467–1503","1480–1525":"1480–1525","1488–Female":"1488–Surnud","1490–Female":"1490–Surnud","1443–1501":"1443–1501","1443–1500":"1443–15